INSERT INTO `wp_gloss` (`id`, `termin`, `dess`) VALUES
(2, 'Cost-of-Living Index', 'A cost-of-living index is a theoretical framework that measures the relative cost of living over a specific period of time.  The framework used is a price index, which is a calculated average of prices for specific goods or services within a certain region, during a pre-determined interval of time.  This index determines what is known as the “cost of living”, or the cost of maintaining a certain standard of living.  The basis of the cost-of-living index is attributed to Russian economist A.A. Konüs, who based the index on the theory that consumers attempt to gain as much utility as possible from the money they have to spend.  Both the price index and the cost-of-living are variable depending on the region, making the cost-of-living index also variable and comparable between different areas.  The true cost-of-living index is the cost of achieving a standard of living in one year compared to the cost of achieving the same level the following year.'),
(3, 'Distribution Center', 'A large warehouse where goods are packaged and stocked for the purpose of being distributed to anyone from retail chains for wholesale prices, or directly to consumers. A company typically has a central location from which products are regularly shipped out to various destinations. Along with keeping up with the demand of goods distribution, distribution centers often handle small manufacturing duties, such as adding labels.  '),
(4, 'Facility Relocation', 'The movement or relocation of a business from an established location to a new region, often overseas. Reasons for a site change can have several motivations, such as the reduction of overhead, the minimization labor costs through outsourcing, market expansion, or equipment and facility upgrades. Businesses typically face a combination of these issues leading up to this decision. '),
(5, 'Electronic Data Exchange', 'Used mostly between businesses, electronic data exchange is a transmission of data that is strictly from one computer system to another. When the information is sent between the computers, it is usually coded in a format not intended for human interface and rarely is there any human intervention in the exchange (unless there is an error in the transaction).  While there are numerous ways that the files can be sent, most businesses use Internet protocols, such as AS2, to help ensure security. '),
(6, 'Reorder Point', 'The reorder point is the moment when the level of inventory reaches a point in which a new order must be made to the supplier. Businesses calculate their reorder point by trying to predict the future sales of a particular item, the shipping time necessary, and the amount of safety stock required within their inventory. The level of inventory ideally never reaches zero due to finding the correct lead-time (the amount of time between the point of reordering to the point at which the items are inventory) and the amount of safety stock (items on reserve in the event of an unanticipated fluctuation of demand) available.'),
(7, 'Cross Docking System', 'A logistics practice in which goods or materials are transferred directly from a distribution center or sorting facility immediately onto outbound modes of transportation, utilizing little to no storage time in between. The result of this method leads to the reduction of levels of inventory and costs of operation, as well as a throughput increase.'),
(8, 'Make-to-Stock', 'In make-to-stock, or MTS, goods are manufactured according to demand forecasts and stocked in warehouses. These demand forecasts are calculated through sales histories. Goods that are MTS are usually in demand during highly predictable and seasonal periods. The use of MTS is beneficial because it controls inventory by minimizing excess stock. In addition, it greatly reduces the cost of preparing for high volume goods.'),
(9, 'Radio Frequency Identification (RFID)', 'Radio Frequency Identification (RFID) is a relatively new form of technology developed for the logistics industry for the import and export of goods. Rather than using the traditional barcode system to locate and track shipments, RFID allows manufacturers to decrease loading and unloading time through the use of radio frequencies to track the shipment’s “codes.” When in close proximity to a transmitter, the small device placed on the shipment’s container sends the product’s information to it instantly, which differs significantly from physically scanning a barcode. This has not become a widespread technology due to the high cost of RFID which most manufacturers cannot afford as an expense.'),
(10, 'Marginal Analysis', 'Marginal analysis is the process in which a business looks at both expenses and revenue for one aspect of their resources in order to determine what is beneficial or harmful for the company’s spending and budget. This method is used to establish a costs/benefits ratio to better serve the economic interests of a given company.'),
(11, 'Shipper', 'A shipper is a colloquial term for a person, company, or manufacturer who is responsible for transporting and goods from one firm to another. The shippers organize merchandise through packaging, labeling and preparing it for shipment. Shippers can be part of a Shippers Association in which various members of the association collaborate and pool their cargo together to get better deals on shipping rates. The official term for a shipper is a “consignor,” although the term “shipper” is generally used for clarifying that the goods are for national postal shipping, rather than international. The proper term of “consignor” is generally used when companies are conducting business together, in order to avoid legal disputes.'),
(12, 'Third-Party Logistics (3PL)', 'Third-part Logistics, also known as 3PLs, are firms that provide an integration of and oversight over all aspects of the logistics process. Some firms will provide a variety of services, ranging from shipping, warehousing, and intermodal transportation, that ultimately assists in the synthesis of supply chain management. 3PLs allow companies to gain efficiency by outsourcing the tasks of ordering from manufacturer to supplier.'),
(13, 'Field Warehousing', 'A financing agreement whereby the items stored in the warehouse becomes the collateral for the lender. As the borrower pays the debt for the goods stored in the warehouse, the lender releases them. '),
(14, 'Supplier Parks', 'Pioneered by the automotive industry, a supplier park is a cluster of suppliers or vendors that are located in close proximity to the final assembly plant. Benefits for this type of grouping include the reduction of shipment costs, quicker turnaround time, and inventory control. '),
(15, 'Fourth-Party Logistics (4PL)', 'Also known as “4PL”’s and/or “lead logistics providers,” a Fourth-party logistics firm is a consulting firm specializing in the logistics, transportation, and supply chain management industries. It is an independent, singularly accountable, and non-asset based logistics provider. 4PL’s give a 360 degree view of all options in the market without focusing specifically on their own ability to implement the recommendations they give. A 4PL firm typically contracts out logistical operations to specialist firms (also known as, 3PL’s) and coordinates the activities of the third party. The main function of a 4PL is to assemble resources, capabilities and technology within the supply chain.'),
(16, 'Vendor Managed Inventory', 'Vendor-managed Inventory (VMI) is a system that improves the supply chain performance by making the manufacturer become responsible for the distributor’s inventory levels. The manufacturer receives electronic data (giving them access to every item the distributor provides along with true point of sale data) of the distributor’s inventory that indicates the distributor’s sales and stock levels. VMI allows the manufacturer to generate and provide the order, rather than the distributor. '),
(17, 'Supply Chain', 'A network of retailers, suppliers, distributors, transporters, and storage facilities involved in moving products and/or services from supplier to consumer. The supply chain process deals with the flow of production starting with the raw materials stage, moving through the trade and manufacturing stage, and finishing with the distribution stage, when the finished product is released into the market. '),
(18, 'Supply Chain Integration', 'Closely related to supply chain management, supply chain integration is the business strategy that links the buyers, suppliers, providers, and customers through the governance of supply and demand. Effective supply chain integrations requires the right employees and resources, trust within the companies or chain partners involved, assimilation of supply chain forethought and decisions of production, and the portioning of risk with reward.'),
(19, 'Just-In-Time (JIT)', 'Just-in-time (JIT) refers to an effective form of goods production and disribution that works to streamline manufacturing and transportation costs, thus enabling a higher revenue for the a firm. The precise timing and details are regulated by a system referred to as Kanban, which allows the company to know what, how much, and when to produce their goods. Many large firms have now adopted or adapted to the JIT method of production as a means of cutting inventory, simplifying shipping, and increasing revenue.'),
(20, 'Consignee', 'The consignee is the recipient of goods in a binding or contractual arrangement between a carrier (a consignor) and a receiver. Official proprietorship of the goods, however, is not entitled to the consignee until there has been payment from the seller, or consignor. Many laws exist to specifically protect a consignee in business transactions. For example, when dealing with air shipment a waybill defends the rights of the recipient by applying all applicable state laws, or integration of laws, that defends the goods until they are shipped to the consignee. Likewise, in rail travel the goods are protected under what is known as CIV, or International Conditions of Sale. Being a major part of the shipping and delivery process, the consignee requires extensive protection.'),
(21, 'Global Procurement', 'A practice largely in use by the early 1990’s, global procurement refers to the selling of goods for the most beneficial Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) after weighing all factors including location, shipment, proportion, disbursement, etc. More specifically, global procurement pertains to this specific method of acquisition of goods overseas. For example, the company Global Procurement LLC, based out of Florida, deals directly with Africa by ensuring that they receive goods and shipments at the most affordable and advantageous prices and times, and in the best possible quantities. Procurement can generally be divided into two categories: direct production affiliated procurement and indirect non-production affiliated procurement. Direct procurement is the emphasis in supply chain management and more commonly includes the finished product of specific goods to be shipped worldwide, while indirect procurement deals more closely with vague items that vary between all price ranges.'),
(22, 'Stock Keeping Unit (SKU)', 'A Stock Keeping Unit is a number or code used to identify a type of item that is for sale. This number helps the vendor keep an accurate inventory as well as relevant information on the item. Each SKU is assigned at the merchant’s level, and is therefore different from the manufacturer’s or other parties in the supply chain. SKUs are also assigned for each variant of an item. If a costume comes in small, medium, and large, there are three different SKUs for the same costume. This number helps merchants locate availability and location on the item in question.'),
(23, 'Break Bulk Cargo', 'A term used in the shipping industry that refers to a procedure in which goods must be loaded individually, rather than in intermodal containers. The break-bulk method requires the transporters to individually add packages via crane onto a ship. The term derives from the extraction process required of individually breaking up and removing the cargo from a ship at port. Break bulk cargo was the most common form of cargo shipping, until the explosion of intermodal containerization in 1956. The new form of shipping allowed cargo to be unloaded more efficiently off the ships and onto the shipping docks, thereby reducing process times.'),
(24, 'Inventory Management', 'The procedures and policies that maintain the size and placement of stocked goods in a distribution center, warehouse, or retailer.  This system of product control is utilized throughout the supply chain network to provide efficient production, sales, and customer service by handling all aspects related to the tracking and management of material goods. Fundamental characteristics of this process include inventory forecasting, carrying costs, value, shelf space, quality control, replenishment, returns, and demand forecasting. Optimal levels of inventory are the direct result of Inventory Management, which is still an ongoing process due to the changes in logistics and distribution over time.'),
(25, 'Rail Gauge', 'The measured space between the tops of the two parallel rails which make up a standard railway line. The standard track gauge for 60% of the world’s railroads is 4ft. 8 ½ in.  Other gauges include broad gauge (wider than standard), narrow gauge (smaller than standard), and dual gauge (tracks consisting of 3-4 rails capable of carrying trains of different gauges).'),
(26, 'Ocean Carrier Alliances', 'Steamship lines who agree to combine and share modes of capacity, terminal access, shipping routes, chassis, and other resources to maximize efficiency. By sharing assets, these companies can send out fewer ships, while still providing products to their customers in a competitive and global market. For example, The Grand Alliance consists of Hapag-Lloyd, NYK Line, OOCL, and the Malaysia International Shipping Company. By consolidating their resources, this group now has access to 337 container ships and has a carrying capacity of well over 900,000 TEUs. Alliances such as this one have helped smaller shipping liners to compete with larger lines like Maersk.'),
(27, 'GSCF Model', 'The GSCF Model is the supply chain model introduced by the Global Supply Chain Forum. It is a systematic network consisting of eight essential elements of business. This model is used to analyze the management of customer relations, customer service, manufacturing, fulfillment of orders, demand, supplier relationship, product development, and returns. This model for supply chain management is a tool for those who work in logistics, production, distribution, economics, research, and marketing. Each of the eight business processes is vital to the success of the system, however the most important aspects within the operation of the supply chain remain management of both customer and supplier relations.'),
(28, 'Logistics Automation', 'An application of software and hardware components that make logistic operations within warehouses and distribution centers work as efficiently as possible without the need for manual labor. Logistic automation systems include fixed machinery, motion check weighers, mobile technology, and integration software that provide overall control of the automation machinery that facilitates the highly tailored logistical requirements normally undertaken by supply chain management systems.'),
(29, 'Unit Load', 'The packaging and storing together of packaged goods, individual items, and items from shipping containers consolidated into one standardized “unit.”  That unit load fits tightly onto pallets, warehouse racks, intermodal containers, trucks and boxcars, and can be easily moved with a pallet jack or forklift.'),
(30, 'Automated Storage and Retrieval System', 'Automated Storage and Retrieval System (ASRS) is an automated system used to execute inventory management in warehouses and distribution centers. In comparison to manual handling, ASRS, reduces the need for human error and is beneficial for the utilizing space. ASRS can also be used in large quantity loads that are constantly moved, enabling control over inventory. '),
(31, 'Warehouse Management System', 'Warehouse management system, or WMS, is used to maintain and systematize warehouses. Monitoring the movement within a warehouse, this system enables control over efficiency. With the use of advance technology such as &lt;a href=\\&quot;http://empirelogistics.org/?page_id=760&amp;termin=Radio_Frequency_Identification_%28RFID%29\\&quot;&gt;RFID&lt;/a&gt;, Radio Frequency Identification, electronic data exchange and other identification technologies, the warehouse management system keeps track of the movement of products.'),
(32, 'Vertical Lift Module', 'The vertical lift module is a storage device for unit loads. It typically consists of many shelves and is attached to a movable lift that moves the shelves up and down. Once a product on a shelf is selected, the lift can easily be inserted into the shelf and be brought down. This allows workers in warehouses to obtain products on higher shelves. The device allows for greater storage capacity and accessibility. '),
(33, 'Make-to-Order', 'A system in which the product being manufactured will only be made after an order has been placed. This process reduces the likelihood of the products over-accumulating as inventory and facilitates JIT production and distribution. Custom parts may be required and as a result will likely increase the price of the product. The consumer’s willingness to pay a premium for these goods and the extended time from manufacturing time required for the product are generally weighed in the cost/benefits analysis of make-to-order production. Make-to-order is also method of reducing costs in inventory management by reducing stock increases.'),
(34, 'Fixed Order Interval', 'Fixed order interval is a system in which orders are placed on a periodic basis. For example, an order may be placed every month, every week, or a certain amount of times per week. The time that the order is placed does not usually change; hence it is a “fixed” order interval. The quantity of inventory being ordered is variable and can change at any time. The inventory must be continually checked in order to place an accurate order. In order to avoid a substantial amount of time between each order, the seller must foresee how much of the product is needed before the next order is placed. Retail firms often follow this model in order to keep the minimum amount of inventory possible while still catering to their customers. '),
(35, 'Gantry Crane', 'A type of crane that lifts heavy objects with a hoist, usually mounted on a trolley that runs horizontally along a rail or a pair of rails attached beneath a beam. A gantry crane is typically used for loading and unloading break-bulk cargo, large containers and heavy cargo. Gantry cranes are most commonly used in ports, steel yards, paper mills and automotive repair shops.'),
(36, 'Stowability', 'Stoability is a term that refers to the strategic placement of goods in a specific way to minimize space consumption. It involves the packaging and placement of freight in unit loads as well the process of arranging and filling an area in intermodal containers, in cargo lines, or in airplanes.'),
(37, 'Intermodal Container', 'An intermodal container is a standardized storage unit that is used to transport goods (both foreign and domestic) to various countries. The “shipping container\\&quot; is most notably able to be transferred from one form of transportation to another. Intermodal containers were designed by Malcom McLean in 1956 and rapidly revolutionized the shipping industry by transforming the break bulk cargo method.'),
(38, 'Nodes', 'A node is a connection point in a network. A node can either be a starting point of distribution or a “communication” endpoint. The node serves as a transporter to different communication channels as it relays facts and figures to different networks by sending, receiving, and even forwarding information. Nodes are also known as servers, clients, or peers: they “serve” to other networks by transporting them information; they assume the “client” role while waiting to receive the information from the networking channel; or, they can be “peers” which serve as both the client and the server depending upon what is needed.'),
(39, 'Shipper', 'A shipper is a company who prepares the goods by packaging and labeling them. After doing so, they arrange them for transit and mark them ready for shipment. These companies also manage how they get shipped and make sure the transit runs smoothly. Shippers are usually considered exporters, sellers, or individuals who deliver and commit merchandise. The shipping company is held responsible for making sure the products are shipped out and distributed where they are supposed to go.'),
(40, 'Paperless Warehouse', 'A world-wide warehouse management system in which an integrated computer and bar code scanning system are designed to eliminate paperwork as a whole. This integrated application functions as a single program to optimize warehousing and logistics operations. It can reduce operating costs and improve order accuracy, speed of delivery, and inventory managment. This method is designed to renovate the traditional warehouse method and focus on complete project delivery. It provides warehouse shippers and packers with portable hand-held computers including radio transmitters and bar code scanners. The individual workers in the warehouse use the hand-held computers to present customer orders, scan, and confirm bar codes. Shippers use hand-held computers to verify and confirm that items are packed and shipped according to order.'),
(41, 'Time Series Forecasting', 'A list of time variables (daily, monthly, quarterly, etc.) that are assigned a numerical value. They are often used by economists in predicting future movements in the variable based on known past events. Forecasting is used to predict data points before they are measured meaning businesses can extend historical values to forecast future data. One example of time series forecasting would be predicting the popularity of a specific product based on past seasonal sales of a similar product.'),
(42, 'Transaction Processing System (TPS)', 'A transaction processing system stores and alters information regarding the transactions of a particular institution. In contrast to “batch processing,” TPS offers immediate feedback regarding individual transactions. In order to be considered a TPS, it must pass an ACID test: Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability. These four steps ensure that all transactions are atomic (either all steps happen, or none do), consistent (each transaction is able to occur from and lead to another transaction), isolated (no operations can interfere with an incomplete transaction), and durable (transaction data must be recoverable from any form of system failure).'),
(43, 'Twenty Foot Equivalent Unit (TEU)', 'An inexact unit of measurement used when addressing the size capacity of container terminals and container ships. Calculated from purely a volumetric standpoint, one “twenty foot equivalent unit” is roughly equal to one standard-sized intermodal container. Since volume is favored over size, a lack of standardization in the height of TEU’s (range from 4.25-9.5 feet) has emerged.'),
(44, 'Bonded Storage', 'Bonded storage is the process of temporary storage of goods in a warehouse facility where goods are placed while packaging, aging or curing occurs. During this period of time, taxes on goods are suspended until merchandise is released from the bonded warehouse. Imported goods are often placed in bonded storage while awaiting payment of import duties or for packaging and maintenance.'),
(45, 'Market Strategy', 'A method used for convincing consumers to buy a particular product by initially lowering prices on high-end goods to build a relationship with consumers. After the initial relationship is established, the company will then sell their more expensive goods on the basis that the consumer trusts the company. With this trust, a company can maintain a competitive advantage centered around the ideal that the consumer comes first.'),
(46, 'Nesting', 'Nesting refers to the practice of manufacturing parts in the most effective way possible. For example, in using design programs that determine if there is extra space on a piece of sheet metal, the company has the capacity to exponentially increase their productivity. By fitting as many parts into one piece of raw metal, costs can be cut and production time can be increased.'),
(47, 'Consignee', 'A consignee is the person or company to whom materials or goods are going to be shipped. In the drafting of the laws of international trade, the consignee must show his or her identity to obtain the package or shipment. However, there are places where this law has no effect, such as Hong Kong, and as a precaution, most packages contain a consignee mark that can be used to identify the goods for a particular consignee. The consignee is fully responsible for the ship and the goods it delivers once it reaches its destination and can be fined for delaying shipment longer than the allotted amount of time in port. '),
(48, 'Order Processing', 'Refers to the picking, packing, and delivery of packed items to a shipper that typically occurs in a distribution center. Order processing begins from the time a retailer or seller receives an order from a buyer to the time that the product is released to a shipper.  Through “order processing”, a seller can inform the buyer if the order is available, the date it will be shipped out, and to what location.'),
(49, 'Private Warehousing', 'A type of warehouse that is owned and operated on a long-term lease basis by the company using the space. There are three different types of warehouses: private, public, and contract. Private warehouses are operated by the company that owns the products coming into and leaving the warehouse. The same company may or may not own the building, but are the only company to conduct their business there. In contrast public warehouses typically have multiple customers at once, and contract warehouses, which rely on a third-party logistics firm to negotiate long-term contractual arrangement with a limited set of companies.'),
(50, 'Bargaining Unit', 'A bargaining unit is a group of unionized employees who are associated with the process of collective bargaining and the negotiation of management issues with employers. By working to improve job salary, benefits, and working conditions, the bargaining unit helps to maintain communication and cooperation between a company and its workers.'),
(51, 'Boycott', 'A structured, intentional movement or action by consumers, workers, and/or businesses to avoid participating in another group or business whose policies they are not in accordance with.'),
(52, 'Collective Bargaining', 'The practice whereby unions and employers negotiate the terms of a contract. A wide array of subjects is discussed in these meetings, which can include: wages, hours, and working conditions. Once the union representatives and employer agree on a set of conditions they create a contract—valid for a certain period of time—that outlines these terms. Employees are empowered in this process because they are able to have some control over their working conditions via union representatives. It is a mutually beneficial arrangement for both employers and employees because it provides a space where both parties can express their opinions freely to the other. '),
(53, 'Contingent Worker', 'A temporary or part-time worker. Contingent workers can also be called temporary workers, \\&quot;temps,\\&quot; independent contractors, freelancers, contract workers, and/or consultants. These workers work for a business or company on a strictly temporary basis. Contingent workers may be hired under a contract to accomplish a specific task or project, work on for commission, or be paid an hourly wage for a seasonal job. Contingent workers are often managed under a system called Contingent Workforce Management (CWM), the strategy of which is to reduce the company\\&#039;s cost in the management of its contingent employees and mitigate the risks a company endures when employing a contingent worker.'),
(54, 'Cost-of-Living Index', 'A cost-of-living index is a theoretical framework that measures the relative cost of living over a specific period of time. The framework used is a price index, which is a calculated average of prices for specific goods or services within a certain region, during a pre-determined interval of time. This index determines what is known as the “cost-of-living”, or the cost necessary to maintain a certain standard of living. The basis of the cost-of-living index is attributed to Russian economist A.A. Konüs, who based the index on the theory that consumers attempt to gain as much utility as possible from the money they have to spend. Both the price index and the cost-of-living index are variable depending on the region. This in turn, makes the cost-of-living index variable and comparable between different areas. The true cost-of-living index is the cost of achieving a standard of living in one year compared to the cost of achieving the same level the following year.'),
(55, 'Employment Cost Index', 'A report of compensation costs that is released in the final month of the each quarter. It is an index-based indicator that presents the changes in wages, bonuses and benefits from the previous quarter, displayed on a per-hour basis. This allows businesses to see the exact costs of workers in relation to the cost of production. This index also includes the cost of pensions, health-care, and death benefits. '),
(56, 'Excelsior List', 'An excelsior list is a document that contains the names and addresses of all eligible employees in a union. The employer usually files this list within seven days of a union election held by the National Labor Relations Board. When an election is held, it is usually for those engaged in an organizing campaign to start a new union. Thirty percent of employees must sign a petition before a union is admitted to an excelsior list, in order to ensure that they have enough support to be founded and functional.'),
(57, 'Featherbedding', 'The practice of requiring an employer to hire more employees than necessary or creating work procedures that are more drawn out, which appear to be time-consuming minuscule tasks. Featherbedding is usually enforced by labor unions, which are trying to create new jobs for the people that have become unemployed due to a technological advancement in machinery that has lead to a decrease in jobs.'),
(58, 'Flexible Benefits', 'Often referred to as a “cafeteria plan,” flexible benefit plans allow employees to pick and choose what benefits they would like to receive which may be tax-advantaged. These options are non-wage compensations provided by the employer to the employee as additional benefits to their stated wage or salary. Some of these choices can include cash, retirement plans, vacation days and insurance options. '),
(59, 'Free Riders', 'An employee that does not pay the union dues or agency shop fees, but still receives the benefits of being represented by the union. Free Riders are also known as “free loaders.” Unions try to discourage free riders because the unions rely solely on the contributions of the members to function.'),
(60, 'General Strike', 'A refusal to continue to provide labor for an employer made by a significant amount of workers. This noncompliance of labor is usually a response to poor working conditions, mistreatment, low wages and/or the lack of quality benefits provided to workers in the labor force. Oftentimes, general strikes aspire for political and economic changes. Although general strikes may begin within the work-field it often gains support from individuals and communities outside the workforce.'),
(61, 'Grievance', 'If an employee of a company is wronged or faces hardship that has caused distress and become grounds for complaint, they can file a grievance with management. This formal allegation of dissatisfaction can be related to working conditions, breach of contract, or a violation in a collective bargaining agreement. All employees are given the right to submit complaints and in so doing are protected from being fired.'),
(62, 'Hot Cargo', 'An agreement in which the employer guarantees not to handle or use the products of other employers whom the union determines are unfair or anti-union. For example, the union workers that are working at a neutral site such as a warehouse could refuse to handle goods from a struck employer. The Labor Management Reporting and Disclosure Act outlawed hot cargo agreements in 1959. Federal labor law generally declares such agreements to be void and unenforceable on the basis that it puts too much pressure on the struck employers to settle strikes on terms favorable to the workers.'),
(63, 'Labor Management Dispute', 'A disagreement between employees and employers, these disputes are often represented by a union or by management. Labor management disputes are more commonly seen during the negotiations of a union contract. This broad term covers all types of grievances that are commonly seen during disputes including strikes and lockouts. '),
(64, 'Layoff', 'A layoff occurs when an employer terminates the jobs of employees due to lack of work or simply because the job does not require them anymore. Oftentimes employees will use terms such as a “reorganizing” or “restructuring” of jobs that has caused “downsizing.”'),
(65, 'Location Quotient', 'A location quotient is a tool used to compare the strength of an industry from a certain region to the national average. If the location quotient is less than one, then the region is lower than the national average and must import goods or services for sustainability. If the location quotient is greater than one, then the region is higher than the national average and must export their goods or services.'),
(66, 'Lockout', 'A halt in production led by employers that hinders employees from working. A lockout is not to be misunderstood as a strike, which refers to the refusal of work by employees themselves. Employers utilize lockouts in the efforts of making it difficult for labor unions to organize an influential strike. These lockouts would end strikes that would have hampered the work of non-striking workers. In addition, lockouts are utilized as a tool for pressuring workers into agreeing with certain unfavorable company terms. In many U.S. states, unemployment benefits are offered for employees who are locked out.'),
(67, 'Median Wage', 'The division of wages into two equal groups where half of employees earns income greater than the median and the other half earns incomes below the median. When measuring the medians of households, families and unrelated individuals are measured together. The median is calculated from people fifteen years and older who earn some form of income. '),
(68, 'Occupational Injury', 'Any work related injury that occurs during a shift. The injury can range from minor injuries such as cuts, scrapes, mild burns, etc.; to moderate injuries including sprains, muscle strains, moderate burns, etc; to severe injuries, which include broken or fractured limb(s), the loss of a limb/amputation and second or third degree burns that occur on a job site.'),
(69, 'On-Call Employees', 'These types of employees are hired with the understanding that their employment is on an intermittent basis typically under special circumstances. For example, this type of employee would be one who would fill in for another staff member who is absent, when an extra hand is needed at any given time, when a company has a peak period, or to work special events. These employees are frequently paid a different (often lesser) amount and are not provided the same, if any, benefits in comparison to permanent staff. '),
(70, 'Open Shop', 'An open shop is a form of employment where the employee is not required to join a union, but is protected by a cumulative majority of employees who act as a union would between the employer and employees. This labor situation is also commonly known as merit shop.  '),
(71, 'Piece Work', 'Piece work is a type of labor that is normally given to an independent contractor who is compensated when the job, or piece of work is completed. In the context of labor outside of the United States, piece work is how many sweatshop workers are compensated, meaning they are paid by the amount of pieces they make for the day. '),
(72, 'Recordable Injuries and Illnesses', 'Most large companies use a medical record called an Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) log to document occupational injuries and illnesses. The OSHA states that all illnesses and work-related deaths must be recorded on the log. All injuries must be recorded as well, except in the case that the injury is minor enough to require only first aid treatment. Injuries that follow one or more of the following criteria must be recorded: injury involves medical treatment, the worker loses consciousness, worker has restriction of work or motion, or the worker has to transfer to another job.'),
(73, 'Scab', 'Also referred to as a strikebreaker, a scab is a person who works while others are on strike. They are non-unionized workers hired to replace workers and to intimidate regular laborers in order to break up a strike.  '),
(74, 'Secondary Boycott', 'A secondary boycott, also termed “secondary action” or a “sympathy strike”, refers to a strike posed by one company who seeks change by exerting pressure onto another company or business. Generally seen in labor or trade unions, a secondary boycott is usually the second measure taken when the first attempts at protest have been unsuccessful. Secondary boycotts have two main types. The first is a secondary consumer boycott, in which the union appeals to buyers in order to control the backing of a business. The second is a secondary employee boycott, in which the union discourages laborers from working for a particular company. Secondary boycotts are extremely limited, and in some cases completely illegal, such as in the United States, the UK, and Australia.'),
(75, 'Shop Steward', 'The shop steward is a union member who is considered to be the “middle man” between management and the union. A shop steward has several duties that include: maintaining the collective bargaining agreement within the workplace and relaying employees’ complaints to upper levels of management.'),
(76, 'Slowdown', 'An action in which employees continue to perform their duties, but reduce their productivity. Workers oftentimes perform a slowdown as a prelude, or an alternative to a strike, in attempts to pressure management into giving in to the workers’ demands, while not officially going on strike (which is grounds for dismissal at some companies).  Workers can still be fired for participating in a slowdown on the grounds of unproductive output.'),
(77, 'Strike', 'Also referred to as “strike action,” a strike is a stoppage of work after a large amount of workers refuse to work. Strikes often take place in response to employee grievances. Strikes are a common tool used by disgruntled employees or the mass public in order to receive adequate attention and rights from superiors within a company or government. '),
(78, 'Temporary Help Agency', 'A temporary help agency, more commonly refered to as a “temp agency,” is a service that provides provisional employees to a company. An establishment will contact a temporary help agency in search for workers for part-time or full-time positions, depending on the job. Many agencies concentrate on a specific field of business including, but not limited to, secretarial, office, warehouse, accounting, and health care positions. Business benefits using temporary help agencies include easy hire, less liability, no clear timeline of employment for the laborers, no health benefits, and lower wages in comparison to permanent staff.'),
(79, 'Union Buster', 'Multiple actions taken by employers, their proxies and governments, in attempt to stop the formation and development of trade unions. Tactics for union busting can range from calm to violent, illegal to legal, and also include challenging unions in courts of law, lockouts, strike breaking, physical confrontation and intimidation, preemption through the creation of employer controlled trade unions or the sponsorship of anti-union organizations. The term is used by labor organizations in an effort to describe individuals and/or organizations. The union avoidance industry consists of four main groups: labor consultants, industrial psychologists, law firms, and strike management firms. The term union buster may be applied to any agency that undertakes such projects including employers who take action on their own, or employers who hire union busting agencies in order to accomplish the same goals.'),
(80, 'Union Shop', 'A form of union security clause in which the employer agrees to hire either labor union members or nonmembers, on the condition that all non-union employees must either become union members within a specified period of time or lose their jobs. For those who object the joining of a union, they may be required to pay that portion to the union for the cost of representation of the employee, but not the other fees for political, or other costs. The clause requires that the employees are given at least 30 days from the date of hire to join the union before they may be fired for failure to join the union or pay dues. '),
(81, 'Unit Labor Costs', 'A measure of productivity that is calculated by dividing the total labor compensation (including benefits) by real output. When unit labor costs are increased, a reduction in profitability for the company occurs unless it can pass along higher labor costs to its customers. These increases in unit labor costs are oftentimes viewed by economists as an early indicator of potential inflation.'),
(82, 'Whistleblower', 'Individuals who inform the public or authoritative figures about acts of misconduct, including dishonesty or illegal activities that may occur within a governmental, public, or private place. These acts of misconducts are deemed as threats to the interest of the public, safety, rules, laws, health, honest business, or regulation. Despite the fact that whistleblowers are protected by the 1863 False Claims Act (which was revised in 1986), they face flack from those they have accused or by other organizations.'),
(83, 'Wildcat Strike', 'Wildcat strikes are also known as unofficial industrial action. These strikes are unofficial because they do not have the appropriate authorization requested from their trade union officials. Through the 1935 National Labor Relations Act, the federal courts have deemed wildcat strikes illegal. Employers are allowed to legally fire employees who partake in wildcat strikes.'),
(84, 'Workers\\&#039; Compensation', 'Workers’ compensation, (or, “workers’ comp”) is a form of worker insurance that supplies wage replacement and medical coverage for individuals who are injured during their employment in exchange for the assurance that said employee will not sue their employer for negligence. Compensation plans vary between jurisdictions and can include many provisions such as: compensation for financial loss, reimbursement or payment of medical bills and expenses and benefits payable to the dependents of the employee if he or she is killed during employment. Workers’ comp was first enacted in the United Kingdom in 1897 with the United States beginning in 1902.'),
(85, 'U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA)', 'The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration is an agency of the Department of Labor, whose mission is to prevent work-related injuries, illnesses, and occupational fatality by issuing and enforcing standards for workplace safety and health. President Richard Nixon signed it into law on December 30, 1970. '),
(86, 'Agile Supply Chain', 'The agile supply chain combines forecasting technology from systems (such as the point of sale system) to determine what consumers may want. It also looks at the system of supply and demand, which focuses on the consumers need and want at a certain time. This type of supply chain allows for flexibility in the processing and ordering within the traditional supply chain model. '),
(87, 'Multiclient Warehousing', 'In contrast to private warehousing, a multiclient warehouse is a storage facility that allows for multiple clients to store goods in the same warehouse. This allows for the flexible usage of the storage space by requiring that a client pay only for the space used. Many companies prefer the multi-client system because it allows for scalability and adaptation to changes in the market. When more storage space is needed for peak seasons, for example, a company can expand without having to commit to that space year round.'),
(88, 'Nonvessel-Operating Common Carrier (NVOCC)', 'A NVOCC (Seariders Brokerage Corporation, for example) is a company that has a role similar to a carrier, but does not own their own vessels. A NVOCC buys space on ships and sells it to their customers. They are permitted by the United States Federal Maritime Commission (FMC) to issue their own bill of lading.'),
(89, 'Systems Analysis', 'Systems analysis is the study of sets of interacting entities, such as computer systems or organizational systems. It is a method developed to help a company or person (referred to as the decision maker) identify a new course of action in an effort to make a better decision than may have otherwise been made. Researchers often apply this method of analyzing a system in an overall context when a company is developing a new product or improve upon an existing development. '),
(90, 'Unit Load Device/Airfreight Containers', 'Also known as ULD’s, unit load devices are pallets or containers used to load luggage, freight and mail on an aircraft. They enable cargo in large numbers to be arranged or bundled into one single unit. Since ULD’s lead to a decrease in how many units there are to load, it saves ground crews time and effort and help to avoid delayed flights. Each one is provided with an individual packing list, also known as manifest, so that all the contents can be tracked. ULD’s come in two forms: pallets and intermodal containers. Pallets are made of aluminum, while containers (known as cans or pods) are made of a combination of aluminum (frame) and lexan (walls). Some containers may feature built-in refrigeration units. '),
(92, 'Workers\\&#039; Compensation', 'Workers’ compensation, (or, “workers’ comp”) is a form of worker insurance that supplies wage replacement and medical coverage for individuals who are injured during their employment in exchange for the assurance that said employee will not sue their employer for negligence. Compensation plans vary between jurisdictions and can include many provisions such as: compensation for financial loss, reimbursement or payment of medical bills and expenses and benefits payable to the dependents of the employee if he or she is killed during employment. Workers’ comp was first enacted in the United Kingdom in 1897 with the United States beginning in 1902.'),
(93, 'Workers Compensation', 'Workers’ compensation, (or, “workers’ comp”) is a form of worker insurance that supplies wage replacement and medical coverage for individuals who are injured during their employment in exchange for the assurance that said employee will not sue their employer for negligence. Compensation plans vary between jurisdictions and can include many provisions such as: compensation for financial loss, reimbursement or payment of medical bills and expenses and benefits payable to the dependents of the employee if he or she is killed during employment. Workers’ comp was first enacted in the United Kingdom in 1897 with the United States beginning in 1902.');
