(1294, 1, '2012-04-20 20:45:10', '2012-04-20 20:45:10', '<p style="text-align: left;" align="RIGHT"><strong><strong><strong><strong></strong></strong></strong></strong> [tabgroup][tab title=RESEARCHERS:] Natalie Moore &amp; Brian Hanson [/tab] [tab title=SEARCH TERMS:] “air quality,” “diesel,” “pollution” &amp; “particulate”[/tab] [tab title=SYNOPSIS:] Although she wasn’t quoted in all of the articles we included in our excel data, she showed a strong presence within her community. The articles show the Aquanetta Warren attended fundraisers, health conferences and community events in an attempt to connect with her community. Apart from advocating solar panels, she was somewhat silent in regards to the words in our search string. In the articles in the Fontana Herald News starting from 2002 through 2011, those exact phrases were rarely, if ever, mentioned. The only similar findings She is a very strong advocate for real estate redevelopment. When she became mayor in 2010, she protested the governors proposed ban on redevelopment firms. Aquanetta Warren’s ideal redevelopment of Fontana would bring pollution to the community. Although redevelopment can create green buildings and housing in the long run, during construction, air quality decreases and particulates increase from machinery. The closest the mayor has ever come to mentioning air quality is her Healthy Citizens campaign. Overall, Aquanetta Warren has chosen what issues she wants to take a strong stance with, and issues involving air quality have not been her top priority. In the area of San Bernardino, air quality is deemed a very important to many of the citizens. Aquanetta Warren has not made these issues a detrimental concern. In over 150 articles, air quality was not mentioned once. Total number of articles in which official is represented at least once as an attributed source: 45; time span between first and last attributed statement by official (2-25-1995 to 4-11-2009). [/tab]  [/tabgroup]</p>\r\n&nbsp;