(2553, 12, '2013-10-24 00:58:56', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'In 1980, two deregulation moves set casualization of port trucking in motion: They were 1) the Staggers Rail Act and 2)  the Motor Carrier Act-both passed with Carter''s signature in 1980. The effects on prices and wages were dramatic, but more importantly it created the opportunity for trucking firms to create the category of "independent contractor," shifting responsibility for maintaining the means of production onto the worker him- or herself. Almost instantly a unionzed, benefited sector of the working class became precarious with shipping costs externalized onto it; trucking brokers acted as middlemen and became the new boss. It also "freed interstate truckers to carry almost anything almost anywhere at whatever rates they could negotiate." At the end of the decade, it was estimated that the total savings to businesses for transportation deregulation was $20 billion and the reduction in wages to railroad workers and truckers amounted to $3 billion (Marc Levinson''s The Box: How the Container Made the World Smaller and the World Economy Bigger, p. 261).\r\n\r\nOther deregulatory changes in transportation had been the Railroad Revitalization and Regulatory Reform (4Rs) Act of 1976, the Airline Deregulation Act of 1978, and even the anti-trust US v. AT&amp;T case which caused the breakup into the 7 "Baby Bells" in 1984 can be seen as part of these neoliberal reforms. And even Ralph Nader, claiming the mantle of champion of the consumer, cheered on this attack on powerful parts of the working class in the name of competition and lowered costs.\r\n\r\nBut at most ports, especially on the West Coast where all the action had shifted with the rising trade with Asia, it meant that the number of trucking brokers doubled nearly overnight. With the crisis that began in 2008, the mythology that these troqueros are small businesspeople has faded, but they''re still in a gray area. By the definition of the IRS (U.S. national tax collection agency), independent contractors set the "time, place, and manner" in how they provide services. Meaning, they negotiate the rate. But it''s the opposite for the port truckers, because the brokers assign jobs and set piece-rates. Which are shit. Some truckers do manage to file taxes as waged workers, keeping them in this gray area.\r\n\r\nThis is because the National Labor Relations Board (U.S. labor regulatory agency) says it''s a violation of anti-trust laws for independent truckers to collectively organize (meaning section 7(a) of the National Labor Relations Act, the right "to engage in... concerted activities for the purpose of... mutual aid or protection" is void).\r\n\r\nAs for Teamsters at the port, their organizing is a scam because the NRLB won''t allow those classified as independent truckers to unionize (anyway, fairly recently the Teamsters still had a $700 initiation fee and wanted $60 a month in dues, neither of which the port truckers could afford). Others who are clearly working for wages also are wrongly made into independent contractors. A study from 2009 called "Comprehensive Truck Management Program: Economic Impact Analysis", commissioned for the Port of Oakland, says "8% of drivers are members of a union" and that "Two‐thirds of the fleet of trucks servicing the Port are driven by IOOs [Independent Owner-Operators] and one‐third by employee drivers." The study estimates there are 1,989 total drivers at the Port of Oakland, so only 159 -- of nearly 2,000 -- are unionized. I believe that Horizon Shipping is the only major carrier at the Port of Oakland that mostly hires truckers as waged workers, comprising most of that 1/3 of the workforce.\r\n\r\nThe massive Los Angeles/Long Beach port complex does almost 10 times as much business at the much smaller port of Oakland. $376 billion vs. $39 billion worth of imports and exports move through those ports, respectively, per year (I''m sure these facts are dated, but the percentages remain the same). In 2008 the Los Angeles Times estimated there were 16,500 truckers at the ports in L.A. and Long Beach. The Comprehensive Truck Management Program study claims that only 1/5 the troqueros in L.A./Long Beach are employees, which means 13,200 are independents (no unionization rate could be found for the 3,300 who are employees). More recent reports claim that the number of truckers has contracted with the economy and there are only about 12,000 working LA/Long Beach now.\r\n\r\nThere has long been a plan to re-regulate trucking at the ports of California, but not much has come of it yet. It usually involves mandating "clean trucks" to reduce the amounts of illness due to all the idling diesel engines for communities nearby and downwind, funded with federal money, but with the crisis and some court challenges all this is on hold. Most of these schemes would also insist that all truckers be made employees and be provided with benefits. Here''s an interesting 2005 LA Weekly article re-posted on the IWW website about the L.A./Long Beach troqueros, the clean truck program, and their miserable working conditions.\r\n\r\nThe Bay Area has one of the most impressive records in the U.S. for mass strikes, general strikes and wildcat actions from its origins into the 1970s. Near general strikes occurred on West Coast ports in the 19th and early 20th century (mass waterfront strikes in San Francisco alone in 1886, 1893, 1901, 1916 and finally the General Strike in 1934) because of the class unity at the ports, when all waterfront workers -- longshore, teamsters, sailors and others in maritime -- fought side-by-side. Sadly, that no longer exists today and most troqueros earn barely above minimum wage, despite arduously long hours. Watch Allan Sekula and Noël Burch''s The Forgotten Space for the scene where the activist does the math and shows that many troqueros work well beneath the minimum wage.\r\n\r\nThere is hope. The troqueros have one of the most impressive track records of wildcat strikes of any sector in the U.S. in recent memory. What they''ve done at the L.A./Long Beach port complex alone makes all other sectors -- including the ILWU which hasn''t had a sanctioned coastwide strike since 1971 -- pale in in comparison. This is my own list, but these are the actions of troqueros on the West Coast since deregulation:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1988 2 1/2 week strike (LA/Long Beach)</li>\r\n	<li>1991 strike (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>1993 11-day strike (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>1996 strike (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>2004 strike, both LA/LB and an 8-day strike at the Port of Oakland</li>\r\n	<li>2005 (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>2006 May Day Huelga General complete shutdown of L.A./Long Beach; 2006 was the historical peak for port traffic on the West Coast and it took months to clear the logistical backlog from just a 1-day work stoppage</li>\r\n	<li>2009 4-day strike at the Port of Oakland</li>\r\n	<li>2012 agitation at Toll Group (LA/LB)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf the longshore workers can take inspiration from the non-union truckers they work alongside everyday on the docks, they might start striking again -- and winning. Occupy''s port actions, while inspiring, were never able to flex the kind of muscle the troqueros have done with regularity. Perhaps a look at the legacy of the troqueros'' will teach the lesson that nothing gets accomplished at the ports -- or any workplace -- without working class agency and class solidarity spreading to all sectors. Those sectors include the whole commodity chain, from the factory workers and logistics/transportation workers in China to the agricultural workers and railroad workers in the wheat fields of Montana.\r\n\r\nRather than the IWW doing a training for the troqueros, I honest think they need to teach the rest of us how to "revive the strike" (to borrow a term from Joe Burns). We''ve already given militant truckers, like Cesar Parra in Oakland, contact info so they can get in touch with radical organizers in LA/LB, like former Wobbly Ernie Navarez. We know people in Seattle who know truckers up there. We''ve got to use mediums like Empire-Logistics to get them in communication with each other. Ernie said truckers at the massive Port Elizabeth in New Jersey are planning similar actions right now.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>ACTION GOING FORWARD</strong>\r\n\r\nDuring the blockade of the APL gate at the Port of Oakland in 2004, the truckers could care less about the media because they were stopping commerce. Once liberal media activists convinced them they should be smiling for the cameras, they let their guard down and management tricked them into stopping their strike.\r\n\r\nOnce a press release goes out, we can be 100% certain that someone from the press agency is on the phone to the cops. This process works with clock-like precision. Hence even before the truckers did the action today, the courts had already issued an injunction over the weekend. The element of surprise was completely lost. So rather than the effectiveness and duration of the strike action, success is judged on the amount of column-inches or seconds of TV footage the spectacular media spits out; direct action instead morphs into press conference and are planned to be media-savvy shows rather than effective, militant actions that stop the movement of commodities.\r\n\r\nThese truckers have proven their class-conscious militancy, so outsiders -- including lawyers, Trotskyists with their platform based on Leon''s 1938 Transitional Program for the 4th International, and union piecards -- should stop advising them and should start listening instead. Every time outsiders try to "run the show," symbolic actions get applauded as victories and the troqueros lose again. Not that we don''t need the adequate legal help of lawyers like Siegel in court; in my experience they are worse than worthless on the picket line. The troqueros already know what to do.\r\n\r\n<strong>ALL POWER TO WILDCATTING TROQUEROS!</strong>', 'On Port Truckers', '', 'draft', 'open', 'closed', '', 'port-truckers', '', '', '2013-10-24 00:58:56', '2013-10-24 00:58:56', '', 0, 'http://empire-logistics.org/?p=2553', 0, 'post', '', 0),
