sive track records of wildcat strikes of any sector in the U.S. in recent memory. What they''ve done at the L.A./Long Beach port complex alone makes all other sectors -- including the ILWU which hasn''t had a sanctioned coastwide strike since 1971 -- pale in in comparison. This is my own list, but these are the actions of troqueros on the West Coast since deregulation:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>1988 2 1/2 week strike (LA/Long Beach)</li>\r\n	<li>1991 strike (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>1993 11-day strike (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>1996 strike (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>2004 strike, both LA/LB and an 8-day strike at the Port of Oakland</li>\r\n	<li>2005 (LA/LB)</li>\r\n	<li>2006 May Day Huelga General complete shutdown of L.A./Long Beach; 2006 was the historical peak for port traffic on the West Coast and it took months to clear the logistical backlog from just a 1-day work stoppage</li>\r\n	<li>2009 4-day strike at the Port of Oakland</li>\r\n	<li>2012 agitation at Toll Group (LA/LB)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf the longshore workers can take inspiration from the non-union truckers they work alongside everyday on the docks, they might start striking again -- and winning. Occupy''s port actions, while inspiring, were never able to flex the kind of muscle the troqueros have done with regularity. Perhaps a look at the legacy of the troqueros'' will teach the lesson that nothing gets accomplished at the ports -- or any workplace -- without working class agency and class solidarity spreading to all sectors. Those sectors include the whole commodity chain, from the factory workers and logistics/transportation workers in China to the agricultural workers and railroad workers in the wheat fields of Montana.\r\n\r\nRather than the IWW doing a training for the troqueros, I honest think they need to teach the rest of us how to "revive the strike" (to borrow a term from Joe Burns). We''ve already given militant truckers, like Cesar Parra in Oakland, contact info so they can get in touch with radical organizers in LA/LB, like former Wobbly Ernie Navarez. We know people in Seattle who know truckers up there. We''ve got to use mediums like Empire-Logistics to get them in communication with each other. Ernie said truckers at the massive Port Elizabeth in New Jersey are planning similar actions right now.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>ACTION GOING FORWARD</strong>\r\n\r\nDuring the blockade of the APL gate at the Port of Oakland in 2004, the truckers could care less about the media because they were stopping commerce. Once liberal media activists convinced them they should be smiling for the cameras, they let their guard down and management tricked them into stopping their strike.\r\n\r\nOnce a press release goes out, we can be 100% certain that someone from the press agency is on the phone to the cops. This process works with clock-like precision. Hence even before the truckers did the action today, the courts had already issued an injunction over the weekend. The element of surprise was completely lost. So rather than the effectiveness and duration of the strike action, success is judged on the amount of column-inches or seconds of TV footage the spectacular media spits out; direct action instead morphs into press conference and are planned to be media-savvy shows rather than effective, militant actions that stop the movement of commodities.\r\n\r\nThese truckers have proven their class-conscious militancy, so outsiders -- including lawyers, Trotskyists with their platform based on Leon''s 1938 Transitional Program for the 4th International, and union piecards -- should stop advising them and should start listening instead. Every time outsiders try to "run the show," symbolic actions get applauded as victories and the troqueros lose again. Not that we don''t need the adequate legal help of lawyers like Siegel in court; in my experience they are worse than worthless on the picket line. The troqueros already know what to do.\r\n\r\n<strong>ALL POWER TO WILDCATTING TROQUEROS!</strong>', 'On Port Truckers', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', '2553-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-24 00:45:04', '2013-10-24 00:45:04', '', 2553, 'http://empire-logistics.org/uncategorized/2553-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
