(2701, 1, '2013-11-29 23:00:56', '2013-11-29 23:00:56', '[video link="http://player.vimeo.com/video/19681653" width="100%" height="350px" border="no" type="vimeo"]\n\n<em><strong>Produced by:</strong> Alejandra Gomez, Jessica King, Maxim Montenegro, Julie Park, Christina Samore, Chris Scotti</em>\n\nIn the warehouse industry, many workers, desperate for some source of income, suffer through unfavorable working conditions just to earn minimum wage. Most do not receive any benefits, and there is always a risk that they will not have a job the next morning because they work through temporary employment agencies. As high numbers of these workers are immigrants, many of them do not know their benefits as workers or do not stand up for those rights out of fear of being fired.\n\nWarehouse Workers United (WWU) was organized several years ago in order to help warehouse workers in the Inland Empire obtain higher wages, better work conditions, health insurance and the ability to unionize without intimidation. Many of the workers are not hired directly from the warehouse, but rather from temporary agencies servicing the warehouses. Immigrant workers often do not understand their rights and lack knowledge of the industry.\n\nMost workers are paid minimum wage for part time work. Yet, without many other alternatives, the warehouse workers hold onto these jobs because it does offer <em>some</em> source of income. They endure the low-wage work, lack of respect, sexual harassment of women workers, and injuries that come with the job. There is a fear to call in sick because managers often punish such workers by withholding shifts. Others fear to speak out because of the prospect of mass firings and deportation—constant threats faced by the undocumented.\n\n“A lot of folks are immigrants. A lot of folks who are not in a position where they’re clear on what their rights are. They’re not in a position where they feel like they’re comfortable standing up for their rights as workers,” explains Sheheryar Kaoosji, who has been involved in the movement. “They deserve the same basic protections as any other worker in United States.” Yet these workers do not receive the basic protections that they deserve. Many have suffered on-the-job injuries and have been discouraged from reporting them, keeping a lot of what happens in the warehouses under a veil of secrecy.\n\nA large percentage of domestic imports travel through the Inland Empire on their way to other parts of the country, making it an essential part of the global supply chain. However, due to employers who deny workers proper pay or benefits, the economy of the region has declined to one of the lowest in the state. Furthermore, pollution from diesel emissions ravage the local environment.', 'Warehouse Workers United ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'closed', '', '2697-autosave-v1', '', '', '2013-11-29 23:00:56', '2013-11-29 23:00:56', '', 2697, 'http://empire-logistics.org/uncategorized/2697-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
